  "why": "The paper’s semSensFuzz/semImFuzz design enforces semantic consistency (metamorphic-style paired mutations of both sensor reading and interpretation, and explicit preconditions on applicability) and enforces naturalness via multiple conformity checks and use of real-world resources (pose/perspective matching, lighting/brightness checks, road placement, size thresholds). However, the tool enforces these constraints on each generated mutation relative to the chosen base test and resource but does not describe mechanisms to prevent cumulative distortion across repeated mutation rounds (i.e., it does not maintain similarity to the original seed across multiple chained mutations nor account for drift), and the authors acknowledge remaining nonconforming cases and a substantial false-positive rate. These characteristics match the “Medium” description: semantic consistency and naturalness are enforced (where applicable) between mutation steps, but the design does not account for cumulative distortion across iterations and does not fully eliminate unrealistic/nonconforming outputs.",
  "evidence": "Page 1960, Section 3.1 (Problem definition): \"A semantic mutation, δ = (δr, δinterp), transforms a test case, t = (r, interp), where r conforms with some configuration of the world, w, into a new test case, t' = δ(t) = (δr(r), δinterp(interp)) = (r', interp'), where r' also conforms with some world configuration, w', and interp' is a valid interpretation of r'.\"; \"We say that Percep passes a mutated test case δ(t), if and only if Percep(δr(r)) = δinterp(interp)\". Page 1960–1961, Section 3.2 (Semantic Mutations): \"we associate a set of preconditions Prec with each mutation δ, specified in terms of the interp that defines whether δ is applicable to a given t. If Prec(interp) is not satisfied, then δ is not applicable to that test.\"; \"we enable the parameterization of δr to employ real sensor data ...  δ_addCar_r could put the car from r_j into r_i ... we use the entity pose, perspective, lighting, and adjacent entities in the interpretation to define the context.\". Page 1963, Section 4.3.1 (Adding an Entity, Conformity checks): \"we add the constraint that the entity must be placed at the same relative physical coordinates to the camera in the new test case as it was in the source test case ... we divide the images into quadrants and consider two images to be compatible if their vanishing points are in the same quadrant.\"; \"if the entity does not have a median value within 5 units (~2%) of the median value of the base image target area, then it fails the conformity check.\". Page 1962, Section 4.1 (Pipeline): \"Given a mutation δ, semImFuzz selects a test case t and queries the resource set for viable resources to perform δ. It then selects a resource and checks whether mutating using t, δ, and the selected resource will generate a conforming test. If so, it applies the mutation to generate t', otherwise it selects another resource and repeats.\" (no description of adding t' back as a seed or mechanisms to limit cumulative drift across chained mutations). Page 1964, Section 4.4.4 (Discriminators): \"We explored this approach, training a binary classifier ... The discriminator learned to differentiate between the classes, but could not differentiate conforming versus nonconforming images.\". Page 1966, Section 6.4 and Table 2 (False positives): authors report manual inspection and nontrivial false-positive rates (Table 2) and state: \"The high false positive rate reflects the challenging application domain to achieve conformity.\""
